# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hsm-key-ceremony
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The **Domain Name System Security Extensions** (**DNSSEC**) is a suite of extension specifications by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for securing data exchanged in the Domain Name System (DNS) in Internet Protocol (IP) networks.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The protocol provides cryptographic authentication of data, authenticated denial of existence, and data integrity, but not availability or confidentiality.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of 2025, DNSSEC deployment is spotty.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The original design of the Domain Name System did not include any security features.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] It was conceived only as a scalable distributed system.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The Domain Name System Security Extensions (DNSSEC) attempt to add security, while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] RFC 3833 of 2004 documents some of the known threats to the DNS, and their solutions in DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC was designed to protect applications using DNS from accepting forged or manipulated DNS data, such as that created by DNS cache poisoning.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] All answers from DNSSEC protected zones are digitally signed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] By checking the digital signature, a DNS resolver is able to check if the information is identical (i.e. unmodified and complete) to the information published by the zone owner and served on an authoritative DNS server.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC *does not* provide confidentiality of data; in particular, all DNSSEC responses are authenticated but not encrypted.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC *does not* protect against DoS attacks directly, though it indirectly provides some benefit (because signature checking allows the use of potentially untrustworthy parties).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Other standards (not DNSSEC) are used to secure bulk data (such as a DNS zone transfer) sent between DNS servers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As documented in RFC 4367, some users and developers make false assumptions about DNS names, such as assuming that a company's common name plus ".com" is always its domain name.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC cannot protect against false assumptions; it can only authenticate that the data is truly from or not available from the domain owner.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DNSSEC specifications (called *DNSSEC-bis*) describe the current DNSSEC protocol in great detail.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] With the publication of these new RFCs (March 2005), an earlier RFC, RFC 2535 has become obsolete.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The full set of RFCs that specify DNSSEC are collected in RFC 9364, which is also BCP 237.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of March 2026, DNSSEC is only operational in 83 (45%) of country code top-level domains.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] ICANN made DNSSEC mandatory for new generic top-level domains in 2014.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Verisign reported about 5% adoption in .net second-level domains and about 4% in .com.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Second-level domain adoption exceeds 50% in .nl (Netherlands), .cz (Czech Republic), .no (Norway), .se (Sweden), and .nu (Niue, but used to sound like "new").
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of 2023, major domains like google.com, amazon.com, and microsoft.com were unsigned.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC works by digitally signing records for DNS lookup using public-key cryptography.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The correct DNSKEY record is authenticated via a chain of trust, starting with a set of verified public keys for the DNS root zone which is the trusted third party.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Domain owners generate their own keys, and upload them using their DNS control panel at their domain-name registrar, which in turn pushes the keys via secDNS to the zone operator (e.g., Verisign for .com) who signs and publishes them in DNS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS is implemented by the use of several resource records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Contains the DNSSEC signature for a record set.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS resolvers verify the signature with a public key, stored in a DNSKEY record.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Contains the public key that a DNS resolver uses to verify DNSSEC signatures in RRSIG records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] References a DNSKEY record in the sub-delegated zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DS record is placed in the parent zone along with the delegating NS records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Contains a link to the next record name in the zone and lists the record types that exist for the record's name.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS resolvers use NSEC records to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Contains links to the next record name in the zone (in hashed name sorting order) and lists the record types that exist for the name covered by the hash value in the first label of the NSEC3 record's own name.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] These records can be used by resolvers to verify the non-existence of a record name and type as part of DNSSEC validation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] NSEC3 records are similar to NSEC records, but NSEC3 uses cryptographically hashed record names to avoid the enumeration of the record names in a zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Authoritative DNS servers use this record to calculate and determine which NSEC3 records to include in responses to DNSSEC requests for non-existing names/types.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] When DNSSEC is used, each answer to a DNS lookup contains an RRSIG DNS record, in addition to the record type that was requested.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The RRSIG record is a digital signature of the answer DNS resource record set.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The digital signature is verified by locating the correct public key found in a DNSKEY record.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The NSEC and NSEC3 records are used to provide cryptographic evidence of the non-existence of any Resource Record (RR).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DS record is used in the authentication of DNSKEYs in the lookup procedure using the chain of trust.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] NSEC and NSEC3 records are used for robust resistance against spoofing.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC was designed to be extensible so that as attacks are discovered against existing algorithms, new ones can be introduced in a backward-compatible fashion as described in RFC 8624.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] From the results of a DNS lookup, a security-aware DNS resolver can determine whether the authoritative name server for the domain being queried supports DNSSEC, whether the answer it receives is secure, and whether there is some sort of error.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The lookup procedure is different for recursive name servers such as those of many ISPs, and for stub resolvers such as those included by default in mainstream operating systems.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Microsoft Windows uses a stub resolver, and Windows Server 2008 R2 and Windows 7 in particular use a non-validating but DNSSEC-aware stub resolver.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Using the chain of trust model, a Delegation Signer (DS) record in a parent domain (DNS zone) can be used to verify a DNSKEY record in a subdomain, which can then contain other DS records to verify further subdomains.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Say that a recursive resolver such as an ISP name server wants to get the IP addresses (A record and/or AAAA records) of the domain "www.example.com".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] When the resolver receives an answer via the normal DNS lookup process, it then checks to make sure that the answer is correct.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Ideally, the security-aware resolver would start with verifying the DS and DNSKEY records at the DNS root.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Then it would use the DS records for the "com" top-level domain found at the root to verify the DNSKEY records in the "com" zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] From there, it would see if there is a DS record for the "example.com" subdomain in the "com" zone, and if there were, it would then use the DS record to verify a DNSKEY record found in the "example.com" zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Finally, it would verify the RRSIG record found in the answer for the A records for "www.example.com".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] There are several exceptions to the above example.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] First, if "example.com" does not support DNSSEC, there will be no RRSIG record in the answer and there will not be a DS record for "example.com" in the "com" zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] If there is a DS record for "example.com", but no RRSIG record in the reply, something is wrong and maybe a man in the middle attack is going on, stripping the DNSSEC information and modifying the A records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Or, it could be a broken security-oblivious name server along the way that stripped the DO flag bit from the query or the RRSIG record from the answer.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Next, it may be that there is not a domain name named "www.example.com", in which case instead of returning a RRSIG record in the answer, there will be either an NSEC record or an NSEC3 record.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] These are "next secure" records that allow the resolver to prove that a domain name does not exist.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The NSEC/NSEC3 records have RRSIG records, which can be verified as above.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Finally, it may be that the "example.com" zone implements DNSSEC, but either the "com" zone or the root zone do not, creating an "island of security" which needs to be validated in some other way.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of 15 July 2010, deployment of DNSSEC to root is completed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The .com domain was signed with valid security keys and the secure delegation was added to the root zone on 1 April 2011.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] A *validating stub resolver* can also potentially perform its own signature validation by setting the Checking Disabled (CD) bit in its query messages.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] A validating stub resolver uses the CD bit to perform its own recursive authentication.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Using such a validating stub resolver gives the client end-to-end DNS security for domains implementing DNSSEC, even if the Internet service provider or the connection to them is not trusted.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Non-validating stub resolvers must rely on external DNSSEC validation services, such as those controlled by the user's Internet service provider or a public recursive name server, and the communication channels between itself and those name servers, using methods such as DNS over TLS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] To be able to prove that a DNS answer is correct, one needs to know at least one key or DS record that is correct from sources other than the DNS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] These starting points are known as **trust anchors** and are typically obtained with the operating system or via some other trusted source.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] When DNSSEC was originally designed, it was thought that the only trust anchor that would be needed was for the DNS root.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The root anchors were first published on 15 July 2010.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] An *authentication chain* is a series of linked DS and DNSKEY records, starting with a trust anchor to the authoritative name server for the domain in question.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Without a complete authentication chain, an answer to a DNS lookup cannot be securely authenticated.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] To limit replay attacks, there are not only the normal DNS TTL values for caching purposes, but additional timestamps in RRSIG records to limit the validity of a signature.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Unlike TTL values which are relative to when the records were sent, the timestamps are absolute.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This means that all security-aware DNS resolvers must have clocks that are fairly closely in sync, say to within a few minutes.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] These timestamps imply that a zone must regularly be re-signed and re-distributed to secondary servers, or the signatures will be rejected by validating resolvers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC involves many different keys, stored both in DNSKEY records, and from other sources to form trust anchors.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In order to allow for replacement keys, a **key rollover** scheme is required.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Typically, this involves first rolling out new keys in new DNSKEY records, in addition to the existing old keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Then, when it is safe to assume that the time to live values have caused the caching of old keys to have passed, these new keys can be used.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Finally, when it is safe to assume that the caching of records using the old keys have expired, the old DNSKEY records can be deleted.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This process is more complicated for things such as the keys to trust anchors, such as at the root, which may require an update of the operating system.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Keys in DNSKEY records can be used for two different things and typically different DNSKEY records are used for each.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] First, there are **key signing keys** (KSK) which are used to sign other DNSKEY records containing **zone signing keys** (ZSK), which are used to sign other records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Since the ZSKs are under complete control and use by one particular DNS zone, they can be switched more easily and more often.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As a result, ZSKs can be much shorter than KSKs and still offer the same level of protection while reducing the size of the RRSIG/DNSKEY records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] When a new KSK is created, the DS record must be transferred to the parent zone and published there.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DS records use a message digest of the KSK instead of the complete key in order to keep the size of the records small.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This is helpful for zones such as the .com domain, which are very large.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The procedure to update DS keys in the parent zone is also simpler than earlier DNSSEC versions that required DNSKEY records to be in the parent zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] A closely related principle is that of **Algorithm rollover**, this involves migrating a zone from one signing Algorithm to another.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] A good example of this would be migrating from Algorithm 8 (RSA/SHA-256) to Algorithm 13 (ECDSA/SHA-256).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Several ccTLD's have already migrated including .at, .br, .cz, .ch, .fr, .ie, .nl and .ph.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Verisign migrated .com, .net and .edu to Algorithm 13 in late 2023.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The migration of the root domain from Algorithm 8 to Algorithm 13 is currently in planning as of early 2024.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS-based Authentication of Named Entities (DANE) is an IETF working group with the goal of developing protocols and techniques that allow Internet applications to establish cryptographically secured communications with TLS, DTLS, SMTP, and S/MIME based on DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The new protocols will enable additional assurances and constraints for the traditional model based on public key infrastructure.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] They will also enable domain holders to assert certificates for themselves, without reference to third-party certificate authorities.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Support for DNSSEC stapled certificates was enabled in Google Chrome 14, but was later removed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] For Mozilla Firefox, support was provided by an add-on up to Firefox 56, while native support was proposed but ultimately rejected.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS is a critical and fundamental Internet service, yet in 1990 Steve Bellovin discovered serious security flaws in it.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Research into securing it began, and progressed dramatically when his paper was made public in 1995.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The initial RFC 2065 was published by the IETF in 1997, and initial attempts to implement that specification led to a revised (and believed fully workable) specification in 1999 as IETF RFC 2535.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Plans were made to deploy DNSSEC based on RFC 2535.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Unfortunately, the IETF RFC 2535 specification had very significant problems scaling up to the full Internet; by 2001 it became clear that this specification was unusable for large networks.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In normal operation DNS servers often get out of sync with their parents.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This isn't usually a problem, but when DNSSEC is enabled, this out-of-sync data could have the effect of a serious self-created denial of service.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Also, public key changes could have absurd effects; for example, if the ".com" zone changed its public key, it would have to send 22 million records (because it would need to update all of the signatures in all of its children).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Thus, DNSSEC as defined in RFC 2535 could not scale up to the Internet.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The IETF fundamentally modified DNSSEC, which is called *DNSSEC-bis* when necessary to distinguish it from the original DNSSEC approach of RFC 2535.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This new version uses "delegation signer (DS) resource records" to provide an additional level of indirection at delegation points between a parent and child zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In the new approach, when a child's master public key changes, instead of having six messages for every record in the child, there is one simple message: the child sends the new public key to its parent (signed, of course).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Parents simply store one master public key for each child; this is much more practical.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This means that a little data is pushed to the parent, instead of massive amounts of data being exchanged between the parent and children.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This does mean that clients have to do a little more work when verifying keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] More specifically, verifying a DNS zone's KEY RRset requires two signature verification operations instead of the one required by RFC 2535 (there is no impact on the number of signatures verified for other types of RRsets).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Most view this as a small price to pay, since it makes DNSSEC deployment more practical.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The new version is published in RFC4033-4035.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In January 2024, a "KeyTrap" denial-of-service attack was announced for all specification-respecting DNSSEC resolvers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DNSSEC specification (RFC4033-4035) specifies that a resolver, when receiving a signed packet from the upstream, should try *all* keys with the correct "tag" on *all* signatures until one of the combinations successfully verifies.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] By putting many keys with the same "tag" and many signatures corresponding to that "tag" in a packet, the researchers can slow down a resolver by a factor of 2 million.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In response, resolvers began to place limits on the amount of verification errors, key tag collisions, and hash calculations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Cryptographically proving the absence of a domain requires signing the response to every query for a non-existent domain.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This is not a problem for online signing servers, which keep their keys available online.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] However, DNSSEC was designed around using offline computers to sign records so that zone-signing-keys could be kept in cold storage.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This represents a problem when trying to authenticate responses to queries for non-existent domains since it is impossible to pre-generate a response to every possible hostname query.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The initial solution was to create NSEC records for every pair of domains in a zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Thus if a client queried for a record at the non-existent `k.example.com`, the server would respond with an NSEC record stating that nothing exists between `a.example.com` and `z.example.com`.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] However, this leaks more information about the zone than traditional unauthenticated NXDOMAIN errors because it exposes the existence of real domains.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The NSEC3 records (RFC 5155) were created as an alternative which hashes the name instead of listing them directly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Over time, advancements in hashing using GPUs and dedicated hardware meant that NSEC3 responses could be cheaply brute forced using offline dictionary attacks.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] NSEC5 has been proposed to allow authoritative servers to sign NSEC responses without having to keep a private key that can be used to modify the zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Thus stealing an NSEC5KEY would only result in the ability to more easily enumerate a zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Due to the messy evolution of the protocol and a desire to preserve backwards compatibility, online DNSSEC signing servers return a "white lie" instead of authenticating a denial of existence directly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The technique outlined in RFC 4470 returns a NSEC record in which the pairs of domains lexically surround the requested domain.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] For example, request for `k.example.com` would thus result in an NSEC record proving that nothing exists between the (fictitious) domains `j.example.com` and `l.example.com`.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This is also possible with NSEC3 records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Cloudflare pioneered a pair of alternative approaches, which manage to achieve the same result in one third of the response size.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The first is a variation on the "white lies" approach, called "black lies", which exploits common DNS client behavior to state the nonexistence more compactly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The second approach instead chooses to prove that "the record exists but the requested record type does not", which they call "DNS shotgun".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The Internet is critical infrastructure, yet its operation depends on the fundamentally insecure DNS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Thus, there is strong incentive to secure DNS, and deploying DNSSEC is generally considered to be a critical part of that effort.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] *National Strategy to Secure Cyberspace* specifically identified the need to secure DNS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Wide-scale deployment of DNSSEC could resolve many other security problems as well, such as secure key distribution for e-mail addresses.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC deployment in large-scale networks is also challenging.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC can be deployed at any level of a DNS hierarchy, but it must be widely available in a zone before many others will want to adopt it.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNS servers must be updated with software that supports DNSSEC, and DNSSEC data must be created and added to the DNS zone data.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] A TCP/IP-using client must have their DNS resolver (client) updated before it can use DNSSEC's capabilities.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] What is more, any resolver must have, or have a way to acquire, at least one public key that it can trust before it can start using DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC implementation can add significant load to some DNS servers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Common DNSSEC-signed responses are far larger than the default UDP size of 512 bytes.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In theory, this can be handled through multiple IP fragments, but many "middleboxes" in the field do not handle these correctly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Yet many current TCP implementations store a great deal of data for each TCP connection; heavily loaded servers can run out of resources simply trying to respond to a larger number of (possibly bogus) DNSSEC requests.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Some protocol extensions, such as TCP Cookie Transactions, have been developed to reduce this loading.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] To address these challenges, significant effort is ongoing to deploy DNSSEC, because the Internet is so vital to so many organizations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] ARIN is also signing their reverse zones.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In February 2007, TDC became the first Swedish ISP to start offering this feature to its customers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] IANA publicly tested a sample signed root since June 2007.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] During this period prior to the production signing of the root, there were also several alternative trust anchors.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The IKS Jena introduced one on January 19, 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced another on March 27 of the same year, while ICANN themselves announced a third on February 17, 2009.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On June 2, 2009, Afilias, the registry service provider for Public Interest Registry's .org zone signed the .org TLD.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Afilias and PIR also detailed on September 26, 2008, that the first phase, involving large registrars it has a strong working relationship with ("friends and family") would be the first to be able to sign their domains, beginning "early 2009".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On June 23, 2010, 13 registrars were listed as offering DNSSEC records for .ORG domains.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] VeriSign ran a pilot project to allow .com and .net domains to register themselves for the purpose of NSEC3 experimentation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This goal was achieved on-schedule and Verisign's DNSSEC VP, Matt Larson, won InfoWorld's Technology Leadership Award for 2011 for his role in advancing DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC was first deployed at the root level on July 15, 2010.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This is expected to greatly simplify the deployment of DNSSEC resolvers, since the root trust anchor can be used to validate any DNSSEC zone that has a complete chain of trust from the root.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Since the chain of trust must be traced back to a trusted root without interruption in order to validate, trust anchors must still be configured for secure zones if any of the zones above them are not secure.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] For example, if the zone "signed.example.org" was secured but the "example.org" zone was not, then, even though the ".org" zone and the root are signed, a trust anchor has to be deployed in order to validate the zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In September 2008, ICANN and VeriSign each published implementation proposals and in October, the National Telecommunications and Information Administration (NTIA) asked the public for comments.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] It is unclear if the comments received affected the design of the final deployment plan.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On June 3, 2009, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) announced plans to sign the root by the end of 2009, in conjunction with ICANN, VeriSign and the NTIA.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On October 6, 2009, at the 59th RIPE Conference meeting, ICANN and VeriSign announced the planned deployment timeline for deploying DNSSEC within the root zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] At the meeting it was announced that it would be incrementally deployed to one root name server a month, starting on December 1, 2009, with the final root name server serving a DNSSEC signed zone on July 1, 2010, and the root zone will be signed with a RSA/SHA256 DNSKEY.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] During the incremental roll-out period the root zone will serve a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ) that uses dummy keys, with the final DNSKEY record not being distributed until July 1, 2010.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This means the keys that were used to sign the zone use are deliberately unverifiable; the reason for this deployment was to monitor changes in traffic patterns caused by the larger responses to queries requesting DNSSEC resource records.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The .org top-level domain was signed with DNSSEC in June 2010, followed by .com, .net, and .edu later in 2010 and 2011.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Country code top-level domains were able to deposit keys starting in May 2010.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of November 2011 more than 25% of top-level domains are signed with DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On January 25, 2010, the L (ell) root server began serving a *Deliberately Unvalidatable Root Zone* (DURZ).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The zone uses signatures of a SHA-2 (SHA-256) hash created using the RSA algorithm, as defined in RFC 5702.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] As of May 2010, all thirteen root servers began serving the DURZ.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On July 15, 2010, the first root full production DNSSEC root zone was signed, with the SOA serial 2010071501.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Root trust anchors are available from IANA.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Underneath the root there is a large set of top-level domains that must be signed in order to achieve full DNSSEC deployment.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The List of Internet top-level domains provides details about which of the existing top-level domains have been signed and linked to the root.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In March 2006, the Internet Systems Consortium introduced the DNSSEC Lookaside Validation registry.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DLV was intended to make DNSSEC easier to deploy in the absence of a root trust anchor.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] At the time it was imagined that a validator might have to maintain large numbers of trust anchors corresponding to signed subtrees of the DNS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The purpose of DLV was to allow validators to offload the effort of managing a trust anchor repository to a trusted third party.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The DLV registry maintained a central list of trust anchors, instead of each validator repeating the work of maintaining its own list.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] To use DLV, a validator that supports it was needed, such as BIND or Unbound, configured with a trust anchor for a DLV zone.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This zone contained DLV records; these had exactly the same format as DS records, but instead of referring to a delegated sub-zone, they referred to a zone elsewhere in the DNS tree.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] When the validator could not find a chain of trust from the root to the RRset it is trying to check, it searched for a DLV record that could provide an alternative chain of trust.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Gaps in the chain of trust, such as unsigned top-level domains or registrars that did not support DNSSEC delegations, meant administrators of lower-level domains could use DLV to allow their DNS data to be validated by resolvers which had been configured to use DLV.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] This may have hindered DNSSEC deployment by taking pressure off registrars and TLD registries to properly support DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DLV also added complexity by adding more actors and code paths for DNSSEC validation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] ISC decommissioned its DLV registry in 2017.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DLV support was deprecated in BIND 9.12 and completely removed from BIND 9.16.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Unbound version 1.5.4 (July 2015) marked DLV as decommissioned in the example configuration and manual page.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Knot Resolver and PowerDNS Recursor never implemented DLV.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In March 2020, the IETF published RFC 8749, retiring DLV as a standard and moving RFC 4432 and RFC 5074 to "Historic" status.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The Science and Technology Directorate of the U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Department of Homeland Security (DHS) sponsors the "DNSSEC Deployment Initiative".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] It was reported that on March 30, 2007, the U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Department of Homeland Security proposed "to have the key to sign the DNS root zone solidly in the hands of the US government." However no U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Government officials were present in the meeting room and the comment that sparked the article was made by another party.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DHS later commented on why they believe others jumped to the false conclusion that the U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Government had made such a proposal: "The U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Department of Homeland Security is funding the development of a technical plan for implementing DNSSec, and last October distributed an initial draft of it to a long list of international experts for comments.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The draft lays out a series of options for who could be the holder, or "operator," of the Root Zone Key, essentially boiling down to a governmental agency or a contractor.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) published NIST Special Publication 800-81 Secure Domain Name System (DNS) Deployment Guide on May 16, 2006, with guidance on how to deploy DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] NIST intended to release new DNSSEC Federal Information Security Management Act (FISMA) requirements in NIST SP800-53-R1, referencing this deployment guide.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] U.S. agencies would then have had one year after final publication of NIST SP800-53-R1 to meet these new FISMA requirements.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] However, at the time NSEC3 had not been completed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] NIST had suggested using split domains, a technique that is known to be possible but is difficult to deploy correctly, and has the security weaknesses noted above.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] On 22 August 2008, the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) released a memorandum requiring U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Federal Agencies to deploy DNSSEC across .gov sites; the .gov root must be signed by January 2009, and all subdomains under .gov must be signed by December 2009.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] While the memo focuses on .gov sites, the U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Defense Information Systems Agency says it intends to meet OMB DNSSEC requirements in the .mil (U.S. military) domain as well.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Several ISPs have started to deploy DNSSEC-validating DNS recursive resolvers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Comcast became the first major ISP to do so in the United States, announcing their intentions on October 18, 2010 and completing deployment on January 11, 2012.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] According to a study at APNIC, the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation rose to 8.3% in May 2013.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] About half of these clients were using Google's public DNS resolver.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In September 2015, Verisign announced their free public DNS resolver service, and although unmentioned in their press releases, it also performs DNSSEC validation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] By the beginning of 2016, APNIC's monitoring showed the proportion of clients who exclusively use DNS resolvers that perform DNSSEC validation had increased to about 15%.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Google's public recursive DNS server enabled DNSSEC validation on May 6, 2013.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] BIND, the most popular DNS management software, enables DNSSEC support by default since version 9.5.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] The Quad9 public recursive DNS has performed DNSSEC validation on its main 9.9.9.9 address since it was established on May 11, 2016.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Quad9 also provides an alternate service which does not perform DNSSEC validation, principally for debugging.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In September 2023, Microsoft announced it would utilize DNSSEC (via DANE) to verify the authenticity of certificates during SMTP communications.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Geoff Huston has argued that DNSSEC deployment should be given up.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In 2016, email provider Fastmail published a blog post stating that the company does not plan on implementing DNSSEC, referencing the many DNSSEC-related outages that had occurred around the time.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] More positive reactions have been put forward by internet infrastructure corporation Cloudflare, which hired one of the founders of DNSSEC to help implement it at the company.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] Domain registry Spaceship (a brand owned by Namecheap) enables DNSSEC automatically for supported domains it hosts the nameservers of.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] In 2025, Dutch registry SIDN argued against the claim that DNSSEC is complex when compared to other internet protocols.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/dnssec] DNSSEC deployment requires software on the server and client side.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] A **hardware security module** (**HSM**) is a physical computing device that safeguards and manages secrets (most importantly digital keys), and performs encryption and decryption functions for digital signatures, strong authentication and other cryptographic functions.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] These modules traditionally come in the form of a plug-in card or an external device that attaches directly to a computer or network server.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] HSMs may have features that provide tamper evidence such as visible signs of tampering or logging and alerting, or tamper resistance which makes tampering difficult without making the HSM inoperable, or tamper responsiveness such as deleting keys upon tamper detection.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Each module contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips to prevent tampering and bus probing, or a combination of chips in a module that is protected by the tamper evident, tamper resistant, or tamper responsive packaging.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] A vast majority of existing HSMs are designed mainly to manage secret keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Many HSM systems have means to securely back up the keys they handle outside of the HSM.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Keys may be backed up in wrapped form and stored on a computer disk or other media, or externally using a secure portable device like a smartcard or some other security token.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] HSMs are used for real time authorization and authentication in critical infrastructure thus are typically engineered to support standard high availability models including clustering, automated failover, and redundant field-replaceable components.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] A few of the HSMs available in the market have the capability to execute specially developed modules within the HSM's secure enclosure.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Such an ability is useful, for example, in cases where special algorithms or business logic has to be executed in a secured and controlled environment.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] The modules can be developed in native C language, .NET, Java, or other programming languages.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Although the highest level of FIPS 140 security certification attainable is Security Level 4, most of the HSMs have Level 3 certification.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] In the Common Criteria system the highest EAL (Evaluation Assurance Level) is EAL7; most of the HSMs have EAL4+ certification.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] When used in financial payments applications, the security of an HSM is often validated against the HSM requirements defined by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] A hardware security module can be employed in any application that uses digital keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Typically, the keys would be of high value - meaning there would be a significant, negative impact to the owner of the key if it were compromised.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] HSMs are also deployed to manage transparent data encryption keys for databases and keys for storage devices such as disk or tape.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Some HSM systems are also hardware cryptographic accelerators.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] They usually cannot beat the performance of hardware-only solutions for symmetric key operations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] However, with performance ranges from 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA signatures per second, HSMs can provide significant CPU offload for asymmetric key operations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Since the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) is recommending the use of 2,048 bit RSA keys from year 2010, performance at longer key sizes has become more important.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] To address this issue, most HSMs now support elliptic curve cryptography (ECC), which delivers stronger encryption with shorter key lengths.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] In PKI environments, the HSMs may be used by certification authorities (CAs) and registration authorities (RAs) to generate, store, and handle asymmetric key pairs.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] On the other hand, device performance in a PKI environment is generally less important, in both online and offline operations, as Registration Authority procedures represent the performance bottleneck of the Infrastructure.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Specialized HSMs are used in the payment card industry.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] HSMs support both general-purpose functions and specialized functions required to process transactions and comply with industry standards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] They normally do not feature a standard API.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] The major organizations that produce and maintain standards for HSMs on the banking market are the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, ANS X9, and ISO.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Performance-critical applications that have to use HTTPS (SSL/TLS), can benefit from the use of an SSL Acceleration HSM by moving the RSA operations, which typically requires several large integer multiplications, from the host CPU to the HSM device.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Typical HSM devices can perform about 1 to 10,000 1024-bit RSA operations/second.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Some performance at longer key sizes is becoming increasingly important.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] An increasing number of registries use HSMs to store the key material that is used to sign large zonefiles.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] OpenDNSSEC is an open-source tool that manages signing DNS zone files.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] On January 27, 2007, ICANN and Verisign, with support from the U.S.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Department of Commerce, started deploying DNSSEC for DNS root zones.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Root signature details can be found on the Root DNSSEC's website.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Blockchain technology depends on cryptographic operations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Safeguarding private keys is essential to maintain the security of blockchain processes that utilize asymmetric cryptography.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] The private keys are often stored in a cryptocurrency wallet like the hardware wallet in the image.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] The synergy between HSMs and blockchain is mentioned in several papers, emphasizing their role in securing private keys and verifying identity, e.g. in contexts such as blockchain-driven mobility solutions.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Automotive hardware security modules (HSMs) are embedded cryptographic coprocessors integrated into electronic control units (ECUs) to protect in-vehicle systems and communication buses against manipulation and misuse.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] They act as a hardware root of trust by securely generating and storing cryptographic keys and offloading security-critical operations such as secure boot, encryption, decryption, authentication and attestation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] In modern ECU designs, HSMs are one of several hardware primitives that can underpin a hardware root of trust alongside secure elements, trusted platform modules (TPMs), one-time programmable (OTP) and read-only memories (ROM), and physical unclonable functions (PUFs).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Their use provides dedicated hardware support for cryptographic operations, but also introduces trade-offs in die area, power consumption and latency, so they are typically integrated into mid- and high-end automotive domain controllers rather than the smallest microcontrollers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Automotive HSMs are typically accompanied by dedicated firmware and software components that manage access to cryptographic services.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] These include HSM firmware, secure boot loaders, cryptographic libraries, and middleware that expose security services to the operating system and application software.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] In AUTOSAR-based systems, HSM firmware may interface with standardized service layers to provide cryptographic operations to applications.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/hardware-security-module] Commercial HSM firmware implementations are available from several automotive software vendors, often as components integrated into AUTOSAR platforms or OEM security frameworks.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] In cryptography, a **key ceremony** is a ceremony held to generate or use a cryptographic key.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] A public example is the signing of the DNS root zone for DNSSEC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] In public-key cryptography and computer security, a **root-key ceremony** is a procedure for generating a unique pair of public and private root keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Depending on the certificate policy of a system, the generation of the root keys may require notarization, legal representation, witnesses, or “key-holders” to be present.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] A commonly recognized practice is to follow the SAS 70 standard for root key ceremonies.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] At the heart of every certificate authority (CA) is at least one root key or root certificate and usually at least one intermediate root certificate.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] This “root key” is a unique key that must be generated for secure server interaction with a protective network, often called the "root zone".
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Prompts for information from this zone can be made through a server.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The keys and certificates serve as the credentials and safeguards for the system.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] These digital certificates are made from a public key and a private key.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The following examples A and B are at opposite ends of the security spectrum, and no two environments are the same.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Depending on the level of protection required, different levels of security will be used.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Unless the information that is being accessed or transmitted is valued in terms of millions of dollars, it is generally adequate that the root key ceremony be conducted within the security of the vendor's laboratory.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The customer may opt to have the root key stored in a hardware security module, but in most cases, the safe storage of the root key on a CD or hard disk is admissible.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The root key is never stored on the CA server.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Machine Readable Travel Documents (MRTDs) require a much higher level of security.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] When conducting the root key ceremony, the government or organization will require rigorous security checks on all personnel in attendance.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Those normally required to attend the key ceremony include a minimum of two administrators from the organization, two signatories from the organization, one lawyer, a notary, and two video camera operators, in addition to the CA software vendor's technical team.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The actual generation of the root key-pair typically occurs in a secure vault, with no external communication except for a single telephone line or intercom.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Upon securing the vault, all present personnel must verify their identity using at least two legally recognized forms of identification.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The lawyer in charge logs every person, transaction, and event in a root key ceremony log book, with each page notarized.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] From the moment the vault door closes until its reopening, everything is also video recorded.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The lawyer and the organization's two signatories sign the recording, which is also notarized.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] As part of the process, the root key is divided into up to twenty-one parts, each secured in a safe with a key and numerical lock.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The keys are distributed to up to twenty-one people, and the numerical codes are distributed to another twenty-one people.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The CA vendors and organizations, such as RSA, VeriSign, and Digi-Sign, implement projects of this nature where conducting a root key ceremony would be a central component of their service.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] A hardware security module (HSM) key ceremony is a procedure where the master key is generated and loaded to initialize the use of the HSM.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The master key is at the top of the key hierarchy and is the root of trust to encrypt all other keys generated by the HSM.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] A master key is composed of at least two parts.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Each key part is normally owned by a different person to enhance security.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The master key is stored within the HSM.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] For IBM Z and Linux One Systems, the HSMs are used to perform cryptographic operations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] The HSM has 85 domains, with each having its own set of master keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Before using the system, the HSM Key Ceremony must be conducted to load the master key securely and properly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] For EP11 HSMs, the master key parts are stored on smart cards and loaded to the HSM with the Trusted Key Entry (TKE) workstation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] For CCA HSMs, the master key parts can be stored either on smart cards or in files on the TKE workstation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] EP11 HSM is currently the only type of HSM that supports Key Ceremony in the cloud.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Both the cloud command-line interface (CLI) and smart cards are provided to load the master key parts to the cloud HSM.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] IBM Cloud Hyper Protect Crypto Services is presently the only key management service and cloud HSM in the cloud to provide HSM key ceremony through both CLI and smart cards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Depending on the key ceremony types, the master key parts can be stored either on smart cards or in files on the workstation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Smart cards are protected by a personal identification number (PIN) that must be entered on a smart card reader pad.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Each master key part owner has one smart card, and only the owner knows its PIN.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] This solution ensures that the master key parts never appear in the clear outside the smart cards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] Compared with the smart card solution, the workstation solution does not require the procurement of smart card readers and smart cards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] This solution uses workstation files encrypted with keys derived from a file password to store master key parts.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] When the keys are used, file content is decrypted and appear temporarily in the clear in workstation memory.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] A key ceremony can be used to generate the private key for a cryptocurrency wallet.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] For Multiparty Computation (MPC), key ceremonies are used to split parts of keys to participants securely.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-ceremony] It is also used in non-interactive zero-knowledge proof (zKP) protocols, specifically first generation zk-SNARK, as they need a trusted setup.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In cryptography and computer security, a **root certificate** is a public key certificate that identifies a root certificate authority (CA).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Root certificates are self-signed (and it is possible for a certificate to have multiple trust paths, say if the certificate was issued by a root that was cross-signed) and form the basis of an X.509-based public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Either it has matched Authority Key Identifier with Subject Key Identifier, in some cases there is no Authority Key identifier, then Issuer string should match with Subject string (RFC 5280).
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] For instance, the PKIs supporting HTTPS for secure web browsing and electronic signature schemes depend on a set of root certificates.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] A certificate authority can issue multiple certificates in the form of a tree structure.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] A root certificate is the top-most certificate of the tree, the private key which is used to "sign" other certificates.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] All certificates signed by the root certificate, with the "CA" field set to true, inherit the trustworthiness of the root certificate—a signature by a root certificate is somewhat analogous to "notarizing" identity in the physical world.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Such a certificate is called an intermediate certificate or subordinate CA certificate.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Certificates further down the tree also depend on the trustworthiness of the intermediates.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] The root certificate is usually made trustworthy by some mechanism other than a certificate, such as by secure physical distribution.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] For example, some of the best-known root certificates are distributed in operating systems by their manufacturers.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Microsoft distributes root certificates belonging to members of the Microsoft Root Certificate Program to Windows desktops and Windows Phone 8.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Apple distributes root certificates belonging to members of its own root program.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In 2011, the Dutch certificate authority DigiNotar suffered a security breach.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] This led to the issuing of various fraudulent certificates, which was among others abused to target Iranian Gmail users.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] The trust in DigiNotar certificates was retracted and the operational management of the company was taken over by the Dutch government.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In 2009, an employee of the China Internet Network Information Center (CNNIC) applied to Mozilla to add CNNIC to Mozilla's root certificate list and was approved.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Later, Microsoft also added CNNIC to the root certificate list of Windows.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In 2015, many users chose not to trust the digital certificates issued by CNNIC because an intermediate CA issued by CNNIC was found to have issued fake certificates for Google domain names and raised concerns about CNNIC's abuse of certificate issuing power.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] On April 2, 2015, Google announced that it no longer recognized the electronic certificate issued by CNNIC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] On April 4, following Google, Mozilla also announced that it no longer recognized the electronic certificate issued by CNNIC.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In 2016, WoSign, China's largest CA certificate issuer owned by Qihoo 360 and its Israeli subsidiary StartCom, were denied recognition of their certificates by Google.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] Microsoft removed the relevant certificates in 2017.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] WoSign and StartCom issued hundreds of certificates with the same serial number in just five days, as well as issuing backdated certificates.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/root-certificate] In 2016, a system administrator in Florida was able to get WoSign and StartCom to issue fake certificates for multiple GitHub domains.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] In cryptographic systems with hierarchical structure, a **trust anchor** is an authoritative entity for which trust is assumed and not derived.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] In the X.509 architecture, a root certificate would be the trust anchor from which the whole chain of trust is derived.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] The trust anchor must be in the possession of the trusting party beforehand to make any further certificate path validation possible.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] Most operating systems provide a built-in list of self-signed root certificates to act as trust anchors for applications.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] The Firefox web browser also provides its own list of trust anchors.
[src:hsm-key-ceremony/trust-anchor] The end-user of an operating system or web browser is implicitly trusting in the correct operation of that software, and the software manufacturer in turn is delegating trust for certain cryptographic operations to the certificate authorities responsible for the root certificates.
